Why do we need this change?
The number of privileges will change at runtime so I thought it would make most sense for it to be a vector that you add privileges onto as PATCHs are applied.

Need some kind of test that verifies that the PrivilegeRegistry we're publishing is correct to the privileges selected.  Based on my knowledge of some of the subordinate overrides, the privilege registry we're publishing can't be correct.  Let's get the deficiencies documented, and then we need to come up with a path forward, either fixing the deficiencies in stacked patches, or marking this with an option flag.

This privilege registry is only missing the overrides. The rest of the mappings can be verified with the unit test. I am planning on incorporating the subordinate overrides in this commit. There is however one singular PropertyOverride in the base registry. Should this be part of this commit as well?

> This privilege registry is only missing the overrides. 

Please point to the test that verifies that.  I'd be really surprised if that were the case, but I'm happy to be surprised.

Before we start, lets get an accounting (with a test) of how many entries need fixed.  That will determine if it's one commit, multiple commits, or needs an option.

The privilege_registry_test.cpp tests:
PrivilegesUsed, OEMPrivilegesUsed, and OperationMap and Entity for every mapping in the mappings array.

It compares the base privilege registry (from https://redfish.dmtf.org/registries/Redfish_1.3.0_PrivilegeRegistry.json) to the one created by the handler.

The only non-trivial fields that arent verified are the different override types.
Other than one exception I am about to note in ManagerDiagnosticData
ManagerDiagnosticData has been fixed in the GET. Now implementation on its route changes are in TODO.

that test isn't enough.  There needs to be some test that pulls the privilege registry, then verifies that the privileges it publishes are applied to each route, for the various roles.  As-written, it will find failures in this.

> It compares the base privilege registry

Considering we have places where we know that we don't match the base registry, this isn't a sufficient test.

This will require a mapping of entity types to uris. Going to have to put https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/59861/10?usp=related-change before implement on GET can go in. Will update this commit with the above mentioned test.
